	body
		header
			.container
				h1 Welcome to CSS Tweeting
				h2 You control how you want this page to look through tweets.
		main
			.container
				figure
					img width="550" height="340" src="https://source.unsplash.com/550x340/?beach,city,nature,mountain,tree"
					figcaption
						small Random photo from <a href="https://unsplash.com">Unsplash.com</a>
				p Any CSS you tweet to the account <a href="https://twitter.com/csstweeting">@csstweeting</a> will be applied to this page. Want to make the font all in Comic Sans? Maybe you want to make the background color lime green?
				p The website uses the Twitter Search API to query tweets sent to @csstweeting. With these tweets wrapped in a style tag, Iâ€™m giving you the keys to style this page however you please. Newer CSS tweets are lower on the stylesheet and override earlier tweets.
				p This concept is a fork of an similar project I made years ago, called <a href="https://bennettfeely.com/csscreatures">CSS Creatures</a>, which allows users to create a little animated creature by tweeting.
				p Some of the HTML tags on this page you can style include <code>body</code>, <code>header</code>, <code>footer</code>, <code>h1</code>, <code>h2</code>, <code>h3</code>, <code>p</code>, <code>a</code>, <code>ul</code>, <code>li</code>, <code>code</code>, and <code>img</code>.
		section
			.container
				h3 Restricted CSS
				p For a small bit of sanity, some features in CSS are restricted. This includes two things:
				ul
					li <code>url()</code> function
					li <code>@import</code> rule
					li <code>content</code> property
				p Otherwise, you can make this page as ugly or as pretty as you want. It only takes 15-20 seconds after tweeting for your CSS to be applied to this page.
